0                                             INTRODUCTION
+                                             INTRODUCTION
-            SPIRES (an acronym for Stanford Public Information REtrieval System) is a pow-
             erful data base management system developed at Stanford that allows you to use
             simple English-like commands to add, modify, search for,  sort,  display,  and
             remove records of information.  SPIRES allows anyone to design and build their
             own data bases,  and a number of software tools exist to make this process ac-
             cessible to the non-programmer.  The designer of a particular SPIRES data base
             decides the names and types of the  individual pieces of information in a data
             base record,  and  also decides which of those elements  will be automatically
             indexed to facilitate subsequent data base searches.
0            Many people in the academic community maintain  card files or lists of biblio-
             graphic references to  facilitate their work,  and may find  it advantagous to
             put their references  into a data base  on the computer.   A  researcher might
             keep a bibliography of articles relevant to his or her area of study.   An au-
             thor might keep an annotated bibliography with notes and quotations from vari-
             ous sources as a  means of filing and retrieving ideas in  the course of writ-
             ing.   A manager of a small library  might keep a bibliography to simplify the
             process of searching for works in the library collection based on author,  ti-
             tle or topic criteria.
0            Storing bibliographic information  in a SPIRES data base  provides several ad-
             vantages over maintaining  a bibliographic card file.    Individual references
             can be easily  entered and modified using  either the WYLBUR text  editor or a
             built-in utility that prompts  for each element value.   The data  base can be
             searched in an iterative manner, using simple ad-hoc search criteria,  and the
             located references can be easily sorted and  displayed at the terminal or pre-
             pared for printing in several different formats.  The maintenance and use of a
             SPIRES data  base can also  be selectively extended  to other accounts  on the
             system.
0            This document describes a computer application that allows you to easily build
             and manage a SPIRES data base for the storage and processing of annotated bib-
             liographic references.   This application also  provides formats and protocols
             for displaying  and printing references in  the standard APA and  IEEE styles.
             All you do  is learn the basic SPIRES  commands that enable you  to create and
             use your private data base.   This document assumes that you know how to logon
             to the IBM 3081 and have a  basic knowledge of simple WYLBUR editing commands.
             Although no SPIRES experience is assumed, it is recommended that you enroll in
             the SPIRES Searching and Updating course, given each quarter at ITS,  or study
             the Œ‡ƒ	Œ Œ„‰’ˆ „’ Ž„›’ˆ manual,  available in Document Sales in For-
             sythe Hall, if you plan to make more than casual use of your data base.
