0                                              Section 1
+                                              Section 1
0                             THE STRUCTURE OF THE BIBLIOGRAPHIC DATA BASE
+                             THE STRUCTURE OF THE BIBLIOGRAPHIC DATA BASE
-            It is recommended that  you read the first section of this  document to see if
             this system will be suitable for your needs before going through the procedure
             in Section 4  to build a data base.    If you decide that  this application is
             suitable, then the setup procedure described in Section 4 will ask a series of
             questions and then generate  a SPIRES data base on your  account consisting of
             three separate subfiles:  one for storing annotated bibliographic information,
             one for  storing journal abbreviation codes  and one for storing  topic codes.
             One of the choices you make during the setup procedure is to select a name for
             your bibliographic subfile.   The names for the other two subfiles are created
             by appending the words CODES and TOPICS to the name you provide.   To simplify
             the examples in this document, I will use the name BIBLIO for my bibliographic
             subfile,  thereby  causing the  other subfiles  to be  named BIBLIO  CODES and
             BIBLIO TOPICS.
0            As soon as you have created your SPIRES  data base,  you can begin using it to
             add, modify, and display records of information.   To use your data base,  you
             must first enter  SPIRES and then tell  SPIRES which subfile you  want to work
             with by selecting that subfile by name (in our example, BIBLIO).   Unless oth-
             erwise noted, all examples in this document will assume that the following two
             commands have already been typed:
0              > call spires
               -Welcome to SPIRES-3 ... if in trouble, try HELP
               -> select biblio
-
0            1.1   THE BIBLIOGRAPHIC SUBFILE
+            1.1   THE BIBLIOGRAPHIC SUBFILE
+                  ___ _____________ _______
0            Each record in your bibliographic subfile  describes a single reference and is
             made up of a  collection of named data elements.   When  entering a new record
             into your subfile, you provide the names and values of most of these elements,
             and SPIRES  automatically generates  the values  of some  additional elements.
             Once you have selected  a subfile,  you can ask to see the  names of data ele-
             ments as follows:
0              -> select biblio
               -> show elements
               Subfile BIBLIO
                ID
                CLASS, CLA
                AUTHOR, AUT
                ORGANIZATION, ORG
0                                                - 1 -
1
-         EDITOR, EDI
          TITLE, TIT
          INSIDE, INS, JOURNAL, SERIES
          VOLUME, VOL
          NUMBER, ISSUE, NUM
          DATE, DAT
          CHAPTER, CHA
          PAGES, PAG
          PUBLISHER, INSTITUTION, PUB, SCHOOL
          ADDRESS, ADD
          NOTE, NOT
          TOPICS, TOP, TOPIC
          ABSTRACT, ABS
          COMMENT, COM, COMMENTS
          SORTVAL, SOR
          ENTERED, DATE-ADDED, ENT
          MODIFIED, DATE-UPDATED, MOD
          SORTKEY
0      Each line of the display shows the name of an element and one or more alterna-
       tive names (aliases)  for the element.   Note that most elements have an alias
       formed from the first  three characters of the element's main  name (for exam-
       ple, DATE, DAT).
0      Once you know the name of an element,  you  can find out what kind of value is
       expected for that  element by typing the command SHOW  ELEMENT DESCRIPTION FOR
       followed by the name  (or an alias)  of the element.    You may abbreviate the
       command to SHOW ELEM DESC if you wish.    Here is an example of an element de-
       scription:
0        -> show element description for author
0        Element AUTHOR, AUT
         This is the name of a specific person who authored the work being
         referenced. Multiple author names may be entered as separate element
         values. If you want the list of authors to end with the expression 'et
         al', then simply enter the value 'al' as the last author name.  If the
         work is authored by an organization or corporation rather than specific
         persons, then do not enter a value for this element.  This element is
         indexed along with the editor element.
         ->
0      The descriptions in the remainder of  this section are intended to familiarize
       you with the names of available data elements and the kinds of values that you
       should supply for each element.
-
-
-
0                                          - 2 -
1
-            1.1.1   Automatic Elements
+            1.1.1   Automatic Elements
+                    _________ ________
0            Whenever you add a new bibliographic record,  SPIRES will automatically gener-
             ate values for the following special elements:
0            ID              Every record is automatically assigned  a unique number as the
                             value of  this key element when  the record is first  added to
                             the data base.  ID numbers are assigned sequentially, starting
                             at number one.  Once a record has been added and the ID number
                             assigned, you can directly display, modify,  or remove the re-
                             cord by using the number in an appropriate SPIRES command.
0            ENTERED         This element is automatically set to the date on which the re-
                             cord was first added to the data base.
0            MODIFIED        This element is automatically set to the date on which the re-
                             cord was last modified.
0            The ENTERED and MODIFIED elements are  useful for tracking maintenance activi-
             ties performed on your data base,  especially  if you are allowing several ac-
             counts to enter and change data.
-
0            1.1.2   The CLASS Element
+            1.1.2   The CLASS Element
+                    ___ _____ _______
0            CLASS is  a required element  that indicates what  type of reference  is being
             stored.   The bibliographic system expects every reference to be identified as
             one of the following nine classes:
0            Article         An article from an academic journal or a magazine.  The author
                             and title of  the article as well  as the name of  the journal
                             and date of publication are  usually included.   A volume num-
                             ber, issue number, and pages indication are often included.
0            Book            A work published  on its own,  usually by  a publishing house,
                             that may be one work in a larger series.   The author,  title,
                             publisher,  and date of publication  are usually included.   A
                             volume number,  series title,  and publishing address may also
                             be included.  Chapter and pages information may be included if
                             the reference is to part of the work.
0            Report          A work published on its own, like a book,  but having a report
                             number and often published by an  institution rather than by a
                             publishing house.  The author, title, institution, report num-
                             ber, and date of publication are usually included.
0            Thesis          A master's thesis published by a school.   The author,  title,
                             school, and date are usually included.
0            Dissertation    A PhD dissertation published by a school.   The author, title,
                             school, and date are usually included.
-                                                - 3 -
1
-      Manual          An instruction manual or piece of technical documentation.   A
                       manual sometimes contains an edition  number and is often pub-
                       lished by an organization.   The title, edition, organization,
                       and date of publication are  usually included.   If authorship
                       is credited to a specific individual,  then the author name is
                       included.
0      Collection      A work  being cited as a  whole consisting of a  collection of
                       papers or proceedings.  A collection often has an editor rath-
                       er than an  author and is often published  by an organization.
                       An editor, collection title, organization,  and date of publi-
                       cation are usually included.
0      Incollection    A specific work within a  collection of papers or proceedings.
                       The author and title of the specific  work as well as the edi-
                       tor and title of the collection are usually included.  The or-
                       ganization or publisher and date  of publication are also usu-
                       ally included.   Chapter and pages information may be supplied
                       if only a part of the specific work is being cited.
0      Other           This reference  type is included as  a catch all  category for
                       works that do not logically fit  into any of the other catego-
                       ries.
-
0      1.1.3   Reference Elements
+      1.1.3   Reference Elements
+              _________ ________
0      These elements contain the information that makes up the main body of a bibli-
       ographic reference.   Many of them have already been mentioned in the descrip-
       tion of the  CLASS element.   All available elements are  described here,  al-
       though you  typically enter values  for only a few  of these elements  for any
       specific reference.
0      AUTHOR          The personal name of the author  of the work being referenced.
                       Multiple author names may be entered.   This element is index-
                       ed,  allowing you to search  for and retrieve references based
                       on the names that you enter.
0      ORGANIZATION    The name  of the organization  that authored or  sponsored the
                       work.
0      TITLE           The title of  the specific part of the  work being referenced.
                       This element is  indexed,  allowing you to search  for and re-
                       trieve references based on title words.
0      INSIDE          The title of the larger work  in which the specific work being
                       referenced is found.   For an article, this would be a journal
                       name.   For a book, this would be a series name.   For the in-
                       collection class, this would be the name of the collection.
-
0                                          - 4 -
1
-            EDITOR          The personal name of the editor of the work.   Multiple editor
                             names may be entered.  Editor names are automatically added to
                             the author name index.
0            PUBLISHER       The name of the publisher of the work.  This may be a publish-
                             ing house, an institution, or a school.
0            ADDRESS         The city and/or country of publication.
0            DATE            The date the work was published.   The value must be a legiti-
                             mate day, month, or year.   This element is indexed,  allowing
                             you to  search for and  retrieve references based  on specific
                             dates or date ranges.
0            VOLUME          The volume number  of a book or a journal  containing an arti-
                             cle.
0            NUMBER          A specific number identifying the work.   This may be an issue
                             number for an article,  an edition  number for a manual,  or a
                             report number for a report.
0            CHAPTER         The specific chapter being identified within the work.
0            PAGES           An indication  of the specific  pages being  identified within
                             the work.
0            NOTE            A short phrase qualifying or  supplementing the other informa-
                             tion about the work.
-
0            1.1.4   Annotation Elements
+            1.1.4   Annotation Elements
+                    __________ ________
0            Four elements allow  you to include additional information  about a reference.
             These elements and their suggested uses are described below:
0            TOPIC           This element allows you to enter  key words or phrases,  sepa-
                             rated by commas,  to categorize  the reference.   Depending on
                             decisions made by the file owner,  topics may be restricted to
                             a predefined set of values.  This element is indexed, allowing
                             you to search  for and retrieve references based  on the words
                             or phrases that you enter.
0            ABSTRACT        This element  may be used to  store lines of  text summarizing
                             the contents of the reference.   Multiple lines of text may be
                             entered.
0            COMMENTS        This element, similiar to ABSTRACT,  may be used to store per-
                             sonal comments about  the reference.   Multiple lines  of text
                             may be entered.   For example, you may include notes about the
                             relevance of the  reference to your research  or an indication
                             of where the reference is physically located.   The file owner
-                                                - 5 -
1
-                      has the ability  to hide this element from  other accounts who
                       might want access to the subfile.
0      SORTVAL         This singly occurring text element  is provided for those file
                       owners who  wish to  include specially  constructed values  of
                       their own design  to enable them to sort references  in a pre-
                       determined,  nonstandard  way.   Most file owners  will ignore
                       this element.
-
0      1.2   THE JOURNAL CODES SUBFILE
+      1.2   THE JOURNAL CODES SUBFILE
+            ___ _______ _____ _______
0      This subfile is a  simple table that you can use  to associate short abbrevia-
       tions with the full names of commonly used journals.  The subfile contains two
       elements:   JOURNAL-CODE,  which is a code that you choose,  and JOURNAL-NAME,
       which is the full name of the journal (or book).   Once you have entered a re-
       cord in this subfile,  you can use the  code that you have defined in place of
       the full journal  name when adding or modifying a  bibliographic record.   The
       procedures for  entering and using  journal codes  are described in  detail in
       Section 2 of  this document.   Following are the element  descriptions for the
       journal codes subfile:
0      JOURNAL-CODE    A short code word or acronym that  you can use as an abbrevia-
                       tion for a  commonly used journal name.   You  should use only
                       letters and numbers,  although  special characters are permit-
                       ted.  Blanks  are stripped  from the code  value before  it is
                       stored.
0      JOURNAL-NAME    The full  name of  a journal (or  series or  collection title)
                       that you wish  to associate with a  journal abbreviation code.
                       Your value should be entered in upper and lower case.
-
0      1.3   THE TOPIC CODES SUBFILE
+      1.3   THE TOPIC CODES SUBFILE
+            ___ _____ _____ _______
0      This subfile is a simple table for the storage of topic words and phrases.  If
       the file owner has decided to restrict topics to a predefined set of words and
       phrases,  then topics  must be entered into  this subfile before they  are as-
       signed to bibliographic references.   If topics are unrestricted, then you can
       completely ignore this subfile.   Each record  in the topic codes subfile con-
       sists of a TOPIC element, a RETAIN element, and a POINTER element.  The proce-
       dures for entering topics in this subfile are described in detail in Section 2
       of this document.   Following are the element descriptions for the topic codes
       subfile:
0      TOPIC           A topic word used to  categorize bibliographic records and al-
                       low index searches by topic.  The file owner has the option of
                       either restricting topic words to a predefined set,  or allow-
                       ing any  topic words to be  used when adding  bibiographic re-
-                                          - 6 -
1
-                            cords.   If you enter a phrase  instead of a single word,  the
                             blanks in the phrase will be converted to dashes (-),  for ex-
                             ample, HEALTH CARE will become HEALTH-CARE.
0            RETAIN          This element is  used to indicate that you wish  to retain the
                             associated topic word even when  no bibliographic records make
                             reference to the topic.  If you plan to predefine a controlled
                             set of topics before entering bibliographic records, then sup-
                             ply a value.  The value can be any character string, or it can
                             be null.   Otherwise, SPIRES will automatically remove the en-
                             tire topic entry when no  bibliographic records have the asso-
                             ciated topic value.
0            POINTER         These are pointers to bibliographic records containing the as-
                             sociated topic value, and are maintained by SPIRES and used to
                             perform index searches.   You should never manually add or re-
                             move pointers,  and you should never  remove a topic table re-
                             cord that contains pointers.   To get  rid of a topic,  remove
                             the RETAIN element  from the table record (if  it exists)  and
                             then remove all references to the topic from the bibliographic
                             records.   SPIRES will then automatically remove the table re-
                             cord.
