0                                              Section 2
+                                              Section 2
0                     USING A SPECIAL FORMAT TO MANAGE THE BIBLIOGRAPHIC DATA BASE
+                     USING A SPECIAL FORMAT TO MANAGE THE BIBLIOGRAPHIC DATA BASE
-            Formats are  special processing routines  which can  be used to  customize the
             manner in which records are entered and displayed in SPIRES subfiles.  Formats
             can either be written  for specific subfiles,  or can be  written in a general
             way so that they  will work with any subfile.   The  formats described in this
             section bear many similarities to the  system format $PROMPT (described in the
             Œ‡ƒ	Œ Œ„‰’ˆ „’ Ž„›’ˆ manual),  but have been created specifically for
             use with bibliographic subfiles.
-
0            2.1   MANAGING BIBLIOGRAPHIC RECORDS
+            2.1   MANAGING BIBLIOGRAPHIC RECORDS
+                  ________ _____________ _______
0            Whenever you select your bibliographic subfile, a special format named $BIBLIO
             is set to control the manner in which you can add, modify, and display biblio-
             graphic records.   To see  a quick summary of the commands  that are under the
             control of this format, type the command SHOW FORMAT INFORMATION,  as the fol-
             lowing example demonstrates.
0              -> select biblio
               -> show format information
0              The following commands are provided by the $BIBLIO format:
0              SHOW FORMAT INPUT   - Shows which elements are included for input prompting.
               ADD                 - Prompts for new element values, creates a new record.
               USING ACTIVE ADD    - Reads values from active file, creates a new record.
               MERGE id            - Prompts for value changes, modifies specified record.
               TRANSFER id         - Moves a specified record to active file for editing.
               UPDATE              - Replaces a transfered record using active file values.
               DISPLAY id          - Displays a specified record in standard display style.
               USING APA  DIS id   - Displays a specified record in the APA display style.
               USING IEEE DIS id   - Displays a specified record in the IEEE display style.
               REMOVE id           - Removes a specified record from the data base.
0              The following commands provide general information about your data base:
0              SHOW ELEMENTS         - Shows the names of elements for your subfile.
               SHOW ELE DESC elem    - Describes a specified element in your subfile.
               SHOW INDEXES          - Shows the names of indexes for your subfile.
               SHOW IND DESC index   - Describes a specified index in your subfile.
               ->
-
                                                 - 9 -
1
-      2.1.1   The ADD Command
+      2.1.1   The ADD Command
+              ___ ___ _______
0      The easiest way to  add a new record to your bibliographic  subfile is to type
       the ADD command.   This causes the format to prompt,  element by element,  for
       all of the information necessary to construct a record.   This method is espe-
       cially useful when  you begin using your  subfile since it frees  you from the
       burden of  having to  remember element names  and provides  several additional
       conveniences.   At each prompt,  the format displays a backslash character (\)
       followed by the name  of a particular record element and  then pauses to allow
       you to enter  a value.   If you  do not want to  supply a value at  a specific
       prompt, press the RETURN key and the next element prompt will appear.  Several
       elements (AUTHOR, EDITOR, ABSTRACT and COMMENTS) allow more than one value oc-
       currence;  if you enter  a value,  you will be prompted  with the same element
       name for another value.    If you enter an invalid value  at some prompt,  the
       format will  display an error  message and  reprompt for an  acceptable value.
       When there are no more elements to be prompted for, SPIRES will add the refer-
       ence and report its newly assigned ID number.
0      You can type a  few specific responses to any prompt that  cause the format to
       take special action.   If you press the BREAK or ATTN key at any prompt,  then
       the format will display the following description of special responses:
0        At any element prompt you can enter a data value, you can press the RETURN
         key to move to the next element or you can type one of these commands:
0        ?          - Type ? for an explanation of the current element prompt.
         \Xit       - Type \X to cancel the add operation immediately and exit.
         \End       - Type \E to add the reference as entered so far and exit.
0        If you enter a backslash character (\) as the last character of a data
         value, then you will be prompted on a separate line for a continuation of
         that value. If you enter two backslashes as a value (\\) then a null value
         will be entered as an actual data value. The maximum length of any single
         data value is 1024 characters.
-      If you have just typed a value, but not yet pressed RETURN, and you see an er-
       ror in the value, you can either backspace and type over the error, or you can
       press BREAK to erase the entire value and retype.  Once you have typed a value
       and pressed RETURN,  you  cannot change that value until the  add operation is
       completed.   If, in the process of adding a record,  you see that a previously
       entered value is incorrect,  you have two choices.   You can type \X to cancel
       the add operation and start again, or you can complete the record and then fix
       the incorrect value using either the MERGE  command or the TRANSFER and UPDATE
       commands.
0      Assuming we have already selected the bibliographic subfile, we can proceed to
       enter a new book reference as follows:
0        -> add
         \CLASS          book
         \AUTHOR(1)      D. E. Knuth
         \AUTHOR(2)
         \ORGANIZATION
0                                          - 10 -
1
-              \EDITOR(1)
               \TITLE          Fundamental Algorithms
               \INSIDE         The Art of Computer Programming
               \VOLUME         I
               \NUMBER
               \DATE           1967
               \CHAPTER
               \PAGES
               \PUBLISHER      Addison-Wesley
               \ADDRESS
               \NOTE
               \TOPIC(1)       cs
               \TOPIC(2)       test
               \TOPIC(3)
               \ABSTRACT(1)    This is a standard reference for programmers.
               \ABSTRACT(2)
               \COMMENT(1)
               \SORTVAL
               -Added record: 1
               ->
0            There are several points to make  concerning the above example.   First,  note
             that the format prompted for almost every element in the subfile, and for most
             of the responses, the RETURN key was pressed to move to the next element.   In
             a later part of this section,  we will see how to simplify the entry effort by
             controlling which element prompts are presented.  After the last prompt in the
             example was presented,  SPIRES  added the new record to the  data base and as-
             signed an ID value of 1 as the record's key.  Once you know the ID number of a
             record, you can use that number in an appropriate command to display,  modify,
             or remove the record.   As a final point,  note that there were no obvious er-
             rors in the example.  If I had typed an invalid CLASS value and then asked for
             help, the example might have begun like this:
-              \CLASS          x
0              Input Error:    CLASS must be either A,B,R,T,D,M,C,I or O.
0              \CLASS          ?
0              This element is used to classify a reference into one of nine predefined
               categories.  You must enter one of the following values when adding a
               reference, and may abbreviate your value to a single character:
0              Article         - An article from an academic journal or magazine.
               Book            - A book published on its own, perhaps one in a series.
               Report          - A work published by an institution, with a report number.
               Manual          - A piece of technical work, published by an organization.
               Thesis          - A master's thesis published by a school.
               Dissertation    - A doctoral dissertation published by a school.
               Collection      - A collection of papers or articles, cited as a whole.
               Incollection    - A specific work being cited within a larger collection.
               Other           - Any other reference not fitting one of the above classes.
-                                                - 11 -
1
-        \CLASS
-
0      2.1.2   The DISPLAY Command
+      2.1.2   The DISPLAY Command
+              ___ _______ _______
0      If you know the ID number of a particular record,  you can display that record
       at your terminal by  typing DISPLAY followed by the record's  ID number.   Re-
       cords are presented in a form similar in  appearance to the form in which they
       were added.  Only elements that have been given values are presented, and ele-
       ments that may  occur more than once have their  values numbered sequentially.
       To display the record from the previous example, we could type the following:
0        -> display 1
0        \ID             1
         \CLASS          Book
         \AUTHOR(1)      D. E. Knuth
         \TITLE          Fundamental Algorithms
         \INSIDE         The Art of Computer Programming
         \VOLUME         I
         \DATE           1967
         \PUBLISHER      Addison-Wesley
         \TOPIC(1)       CS
         \TOPIC(2)       TEST
         \ABSTRACT(1)    This is a standard reference for programmers.
         \ENTERED        07/01/83
         \MODIFIED       07/01/83
         ->
0      Note that the topic words,  which were originally entered in lower case,  have
       been translated to upper case.   Note also  that the ENTERED and MODIFIED ele-
       ments, generated automatically by SPIRES,  are now displayed.   References can
       also be displayed in APA or IEEE format,   and the commands for doing this are
       described in Section 3.3.   In certain special cases,  the owner of a file may
       arrange it so that you automatically see records in either APA or IEEE styles.
       If this is the case,  you will have to type the command USING PLAIN DISPLAY to
       see a record in the format described above.
-
       2.1.3   The MERGE Command
+      2.1.3   The MERGE Command
+              ___ _____ _______
0      The MERGE command operates  in a manner similar to the  ADD command.   You are
       prompted element by element to add,  replace,  or remove values in an existing
       record.   To start the merge process,  type MERGE followed by the ID number of
       the record you wish to modify.   For elements that can have only a single val-
       ue, the format will display the old value (if one exists)  and then prompt for
       a replacement value.   If you press the RETURN key,  the old value will be re-
       tained.   For elements that can have more than one value, the format will dis-
       play all the old values and their occurrence numbers (if they exist)  and then
       prompt for a replacement  for the first value.   If you  press the RETURN key,
-                                          - 12 -
1
-            the  old first  value  will be  retained  and  the format  will  prompt for  a
             replacement for the second value, and so forth.   When prompts have been given
             for all previously existing values,  the format  will then prompt for an addi-
             tional value,  thus providing a way to  append new values to the existing val-
             ues.
0            As with the  ADD operation,  a number  of special responses are  recognized at
             each prompt.   If you press the BREAK or  ATTN key at a prompt,  the following
             description of special responses will be presented:
0              At any element prompt you can enter a new value to replace the displayed
               value, you can press the RETURN key to retain the old value and continue
               at the next prompt, or you can type one of the following commands:
0                ?             - Type ? for an explanation of the current element prompt.
                \Xit           - Type \X to cancel the merge operation immediately and exit.
                \End           - Type \E to accept all changes entered so far and exit.
                \Next          - Type \N to skip immediately to the next element prompt.
                \Append        - Type \A to skip to the new-value prompt for the element.
                \Remove        - Type \R to remove the old value referred to by the prompt.
                \Change\x\y\   - Type \C\x\y\ to change 'x' to 'y' in the current value.
0              If you enter a backslash character (\) as the last character of  a  data
               value,  then  you will be prompted on a separate line for a continuation
               of that value. If you enter two backslashes as a value (\\) then a  null
               value will be entered as an actual data value. The maximum length of any
               single data value is 1024 characters.
0            The \A and \N  responses are useful for skipping over  the replacement prompts
             for elements with many values.   The \A  response allows you to quickly append
             new values, and \N gets you directly to the next element.  The \C response al-
             lows you to correct simple spelling errors  without having to retype an entire
             value.
0            To demonstrate the MERGE operation, we try to make some changes in our example
             record as follows:
0              -> merge 1
               \ID.............1
               \CLASS..........Book
               \CLASS
               \AUTHOR(1)......D. E. Knuth
               \AUTHOR(1)
               \AUTHOR(2)
               \ORGANIZATION
               \EDITOR(1)
               \TITLE..........Fundamental Algorithms
               \TITLE          Seminumerical Algorithms
               \INSIDE.........The Art of Computer Programming
               \INSIDE
               \VOLUME.........I
               \VOLUME         II
               \NUMBER
               \DATE...........1967
0                                                - 13 -
1
-        \DATE           1969
         \CHAPTER
         \PAGES
         \PUBLISHER......Addison-Wesley
         \PUBLISHER
         \ADDRESS
         \NOTE
         \TOPIC(1).......CS
         \TOPIC(2).......TEST
         \TOPIC(1)       \a
         \TOPIC(3)       computers
         \TOPIC(4)
         \ABSTRACT(1)....This is a standard reference for programmers.
         \ABSTRACT(1)    \r
         \ABSTRACT(2)    \e
         ->
0      Note that  existing element  values were highlighted  by being  connected with
       dots to their element names.   Replacement  values were entered for the TITLE,
       VOLUME and DATE elements,  and the RETURN key was pressed at most of the other
       prompts.   The special command \A was entered for TOPIC, causing the format to
       bypass replacement prompting  for the existing topic values.    The \R command
       caused the single occurrence of ABSTRACT to  be removed.   The \E command then
       caused SPIRES to accept all changes made and halt the prompting process.
0      To see how the modified record looks now,  we can use the DISPLAY command,  as
       follows:
0        -> display 1
0        \ID             1
         \CLASS          Book
         \AUTHOR(1)      D. E. Knuth
         \TITLE          Seminumerical Algorithms
         \INSIDE         The Art of Computer Programming
         \VOLUME         II
         \DATE           1969
         \PUBLISHER      Addison-Wesley
         \TOPIC(1)       CS
         \TOPIC(2)       TEST
         \TOPIC(3)       COMPUTERS
         \ENTERED        07/01/83
         \MODIFIED       07/01/83
         ->
-
-
-
-                                          - 14 -
1
-            2.1.4   Controlling Element Prompting
+            2.1.4   Controlling Element Prompting
+                    ___________ _______ _________
0            The examples of the ADD and MERGE  commands in the previous sections have been
             presented exactly as they would appear if  you were to select your subfile and
             try the examples.   When you select your subfile, the format initially assumes
             that you want to be prompted for all reference elements.   In practice,  it is
             more efficient to tell  the format to only prompt for  those elements that you
             expect to provide values for.   You do this by typing the command SET FORMAT *
             followed immediately by an indication of which elements you want included dur-
             ing prompting.   The format reads your  specification and remembers which ele-
             ments you have requested.  If you make an error in the specification, the pre-
             vious element selection settings are retained.
0            The simplest element setting specification is to include the name of a partic-
             ular bibliographic reference CLASS (Article,  Book,  Report,  Manual,  Thesis,
             Dissertation, Collection, Incollection, or Other).  The format knows what ele-
             ments are reasonable to include for each of these classes, and establishes the
             settings accordingly.   If you enter a CLASS name,  it must immediately follow
             the SET FORMAT * command and can be abbreviated to a single character.
0            Once you start changing the element settings,   you might want to to know what
             element settings are currently in effect.  At any time, you can ask the format
             to remind you what elements are included and excluded from prompting by typing
             the command SHOW FORMAT INPUT.   In  the following example,  we establish set-
             tings for the Article reference class and then ask to see the settings:
0              -> set format * article
               -> show format input
0              The following elements are now INCLUDED during ADD and MERGE prompting:
0                CLASS          AUTHOR         ORGANIZATION   TITLE          INSIDE
                 VOLUME         NUMBER         DATE           PAGES          NOTE
0              The following elements are now EXCLUDED during ADD and MERGE prompting:
0                EDITOR         CHAPTER        PUBLISHER      ADDRESS        TOPIC
                 ABSTRACT       COMMENT        SORTVAL
0              To control which elements will be presented during ADD and MERGE
               prompting, type the command SET FORMAT * followed immediately by a
               list of element names, separated by blanks.  Instead of an element
               list, you can type ALL to include all elements, or type a reference
               class name to include elements appropriate to that class.  If you
               type a plus or minus sign followed by a list, then elements will be
               included or excluded relative to the current settings.  If you make
               an error, previous settings are retained.  The formal syntax of the
               command is:
0              SET FORMAT * [elements|class|ALL] [ + elements] [ - elements]
               ->
-
0                                                - 15 -
1
-      This example  summarizes the procedure for  forming a more  complex specifica-
       tion.   Instead of a CLASS name,  you can type a list of the specific elements
       that you want included,  and elements not  appearing in the list will be auto-
       matically excluded.   If you want all elements  to be included again,  you can
       type the special keyword ALL.   Finally,  to cause specific elements to be in-
       cluded or excluded individually, place a plus or minus sign before the list of
       element names.    The following  annotated examples  demonstrate some  typical
       specifications:
0        -> set format * article + top abs
0           (includes article elements plus topic and abstract)
0        -> set format * aut tit ins vol num dat
0           (include author, title, inside, volume, number, and date)
0        -> set format * - vol num
0           (excludes volume and number from current settings)
0        -> set format all - org edi sortval
0           (includes all elements except organization, editor, and sortval)
0        -> set format *
0           (same as SET FORMAT * ALL)
0      To demonstrate the extent to which a carefully chosen element setting specifi-
       cation can simplify the merge process,  we can take our example record and re-
       turn it to its original form with the following commands:
0        -> set format * tit vol dat top abs
         -> merge 1
         \ID.............1
         \TITLE..........Seminumerical Algorithms
         \TITLE          Fundamental Algorithms
         \VOLUME.........II
         \VOLUME         I
         \DATE...........1969
         \DATE           1967
         \TOPIC(1).......CS
         \TOPIC(2).......TEST
         \TOPIC(3).......COMPUTERS
         \TOPIC(1)
         \TOPIC(2)
         \TOPIC(3)       \r
         \TOPIC(4)
         \ABSTRACT(1)    This is a standard reference for programmers.
         \ABSTRACT(2)
         ->
-
                                           - 16 -
1
-            2.1.5   The USING ACTIVE ADD Command
+            2.1.5   The USING ACTIVE ADD Command
+                    ___ _____ ______ ___ _______
0            We have seen how  to add and modify bibliographic records  using commands that
             prompt for values.    The advantage of such  a prompting strategy is  that the
             format remembers  the names of  elements and  can provide error  detection and
             help instantaneously.   The  disadvantage is that you are often  forced to re-
             spond to extraneous prompts or to learn to control and keep track of which el-
             ements are included for prompting.   The  commands introduced in the remainder
             of this section describe an alternative strategy for adding and modifying bib-
             liographic records  that allows you  to prepare  records in the  WYLBUR active
             file and then move them into the data base.   The discussion and examples pre-
             sume that you are  already familiar with the WYLBUR editing  commands for col-
             lecting, deleting, and modifying lines of text in your active file.
0            To add a new bibliographic record using this technique,  first collect in your
             active file the  reference information by using WYLBUR  editing commands.   To
             enter each piece of element data in your active file,  collect a line that be-
             gins with a backslash character (\),  followed immediately by an element name,
             followed by one or more blanks,  followed  by the value that you are providing
             for that element.   The element value  can actually continue for several lines
             and is terminated when the backslash character  that starts a new element name
             is encountered or when the end of  the active file is reached.   The backslash
             does not actually  have to be placed in  column one and data  for several ele-
             ments could be combined on a single line,   but in practice it is more conven-
             ient to enter one element per line.
0            When all of the information for a new record is in your active file, press the
             BREAK key to get out of WYLBUR collect  mode,  and then type the command USING
             ACTIVE ADD.  SPIRES will attempt to build a new record from the information in
             your active file,  and will report the ID number for the new record if the add
             operation is successful.  If SPIRES finds an invalid value for an element (for
             example,  1/32/83 is an invalid date),  an  error message is displayed and the
             reference is not added.    Correct the line in the active  file and type USING
             ACTIVE ADD again.
0            The following example demonstrates this process:
0              -> collect clear
                   1. >  \class article
                   2. >  \title Toads of the Wild West
                   3. >  \author Jeff Mapes
                   4. >  \inside Toad Gazette
                   5. >  \date June 1983
                   6. >  \topic animals
                   7. >  ***                                 <BREAK key pressed>
               -> using active add
               -Added record: 2
               ->
0            The disadvantage of this  method of adding records is that  you need to supply
             the names of elements.   The advantages are that you can enter the elements in
             any order and you  need only deal with the elements that  you have values for.
             This method of adding  records is also slightly less expensive  than using the
-                                                - 17 -
1
-      prompting  method.    If  you  need to  refresh  your  memory  concerning  the
       description of a particular element,  you can always use the SHOW ELEMENTS and
       SHOW ELEMENT DESCRIPTION commands, as in the following example:
0        -> show elem desc date
0        Element DATE, DAT
         This is the date when the work being referenced was published.  The
         value must be a legitimate day, month, or year.  Examples of valid dates
         include '1970', 'June 1981', and '12/25/82'.  Note that a date value like
         'Fall 1979' is not valid.  This element is indexed.
         ->
-
0      2.1.6   The TRANSFER and UPDATE Commands
+      2.1.6   The TRANSFER and UPDATE Commands
+              ___ ________ ___ ______ ________
0      This procedure for modifying a record is similiar to that for adding a new re-
       cord, described in the previous subsection.   The first step is to move a copy
       of the record you  wish to modify into your active file  by typing the command
       TRANSFER followed by the ID number of the desired record.  When a copy of that
       reference is in your active file, you can use WYLBUR editing commands to modi-
       fy existing  values or to  add and delete pairs  of element names  and values.
       When you have completed your modifications, type the command UPDATE to replace
       the old version of the record with the  new version.   If the update fails and
       error messages are displayed, you should locate the errors, correct them,  and
       then type UPDATE again.
0      The following example demonstrates this procedure:
0        -> transfer 2
             1.    \ID            2
             2.    \CLASS         Article
             3.    \AUTHOR(1)     Jeff Mapes
             4.    \TITLE         Toads of the Wild West
             5.    \INSIDE        Toad Gazette
             6.    \DATE          June 1983
             7.    \TOPIC(1)      ANIMALS
             8.    \ENTERED       07/01/83
             9.    \MODIFIED      07/01/83
         -> modify 4
             4.    \TITLE         Toads of the Wild West
            MODS>                              rWestern World
             4.    \TITLE         Toads of the Western World
            MODS>
         -> insert 7.1
            7.1 >  \topic test
         -> update
         ->
0      Note that after you type the TRANSFER command,  SPIRES moves the record to the
       active file and then automatically lists the  active file.   You can press the
-                                          - 18 -
1
-            BREAK key to stop  the listing or you can SET NOLIST to  turn off this listing
             feature.
0            To convince yourself that your modifications were accepted,  you could display
             the record as follows:
0              -> display 2
0              \ID            2
               \CLASS         Article
               \AUTHOR(1)     Jeff Mapes
               \TITLE         Toads of the Western World
               \INSIDE        Toad Gazette
               \DATE          June 1983
               \TOPIC(1)      ANIMALS
               \TOPIC(2)      TEST
               \ENTERED       07/01/83
               \MODIFIED      07/01/83
               ->
-
0            2.1.7   The REMOVE Command
+            2.1.7   The REMOVE Command
+                    ___ ______ _______
0            This basic SPIRES command is included in  this section to complete the discus-
             sion of commands for managing your bibliographic  data base.   To erase a par-
             ticular record from your bibliographic subfile, type REMOVE followed by the ID
             number of the chosen record.   The record will  seem to vanish,  but a copy of
             the record  will remain hidden  within your subfile  until the next  time your
             file is processed (shortly after midnight each night).  This means that if you
             change your mind, you can recover the removed record if you take action before
             your file is  processed.   The procedures for recovering  removed records (and
             old copies of modified records)  are discussed in the Œ‡ƒ	Œ Œ„‰’ˆ „’ Ž-
             „›’ˆ manual, available in Document Sales in Forsythe Hall.
-
0            2.2   MANAGING JOURNAL TABLE RECORDS
+            2.2   MANAGING JOURNAL TABLE RECORDS
+                  ________ _______ _____ _______
0            Your bibliographic subfile  has an associated auxiliary subfile  which you can
             use to define abbreviation codes to represent commonly used names of journals.
             Whenever  you select  your  journal codes  subfile,   a  special format  named
             $BIBLIO.CODES is set to control the manner in which you can add,  modify,  and
             display journal codes records.    To see a quick summary of  the commands that
             are  under  the  control  of  this  format,   type  the  command  SHOW  FORMAT
             INFORMATION, as the following example demonstrates.
0              -> select biblio codes
               -> show format information
0              The following commands are provided by the $BIBLIO.CODES format:
-                                                - 19 -
1
-        ADD               - Prompts for new element values, creates a new record.
         USING ACTIVE ADD  - Reads values from active file, creates a new record.
         MERGE code        - Prompts for value changes, modifies specified record.
         TRANSFER code     - Moves a specified record to active file for editing.
         UPDATE            - Replaces a transfered record using active file values.
         DISPLAY code      - Displays a specified record in standard display style.
         REMOVE code       - Removes a specified record from the data base.
0        The following commands provide general information about your data base:
0        SHOW ELEMENTS       - Shows the names of elements for your subfile.
         SHOW ELE DESC elem  - Describes a specified element in your subfile.
         ->
0      The above commands operate in exactly the  same manner as the commands availa-
       ble for the bibliographic subfile,  but the  only elements in this subfile are
       named JOURNAL-CODE and JOURNAL-NAME.   Because of the simple structure of this
       subfile,  the ADD,  MERGE,  DISPLAY,  and  REMOVE commands handle most of your
       needs.   The following example demonstrates how to add, modify,  and display a
       journal code record:
0        -> select biblio codes
         -> add
0        \JOURNAL-CODE   jaes
         \JOURNAL-NAME   Journal of the Acoustical Engineering Society
         -> merge jaes
0        \JOURNAL-CODE...JAES
         \JOURNAL-NAME...Journal of the Acoustical Engineering Society
         \JOURNAL-NAME   Journal of the Audio Engineering Society
         -> display jaes
0        \JOURNAL-CODE   JAES
         \JOURNAL-NAME   Journal of the Audio Engineering Society
         ->
0      In this subfile, the JOURNAL-CODE element is the key of the record, and can be
       used to identify the record in the MERGE and DISPLAY commands.   To remove the
       record shown above,  you could type REMOVE JAES and that code would be removed
       from the subfile.
0      The advantage in defining abbreviation codes for journal names is that you can
       then use  those codes  directly when adding  and modifiying  bibliographic re-
       cords.   The  element named INSIDE within  the bibliographic subfile  is where
       journal names are normally entered.  When entering a value for the INSIDE ele-
       ment, if you enter an at-sign character (@)  followed immediately by a journal
       code,  the format will search the journal codes subfile and retrieve the asso-
       ciated journal name, as in the following example:
0        -> select biblio
         -> set format * title inside
         -> add
-                                          - 20 -
1
-              \CLASS          article
               \TITLE          An Analysis of Toad Songs
               \INSIDE         @jaes
               -Added record: 3
0              -> display 3
0              \ID             3
               \CLASS          Article
               \TITLE          An Analysis of Toad Songs
               \INSIDE         Journal of the Audio Engineering Society
               ->
0            The final example in this section shows how you can produce a nicely formatted
             alphabetic table of your journal codes and names.  The sequence of commands to
             do this are:
0              -> select biblio codes
               -> set nolist
               -> /set length 102
               -> set format $report journal-code(12) journal-name(25)
               -> for subfile
               +> in active display all
               +> endfor
               -> print unn cc forms=bond chars=cu12
0            If you want  to continue adding or  modifying journal codes after  doing this,
             you must select your codes subfile again to restore the proper format.
-
0            2.3   MANAGING TOPICS TABLE RECORDS
+            2.3   MANAGING TOPICS TABLE RECORDS
+                  ________ ______ _____ _______
0            Associated with  your bibliographic subfile is  an auxiliary subfile  in which
             you can store a  controlled set of topic words and phrases  that can be subse-
             quently used to  categorize bibliographic records.   The  file owner initially
             determines whether or not topics will be  restricted to a predefined set.   If
             topics are unrestricted,  then there is no need to pay attention to the topics
             table.   If topics are restricted,  then each  topic must be entered into this
             table before it can be used in a bibliographic record.  The decision of wheth-
             er or not to restrict topics can also be reversed by following a procedure de-
             scribed in Section 4.
0            Whenever  you  select your  topics  table  subfile,   a special  format  named
             $BIBLIO.TOPICS is set to control the manner in which you can add, modify,  and
             display topics table records.  To see a quick summary of the commands that are
             under  the control  of  this  format you  can  type  the command  SHOW  FORMAT
             INFORMATION, as the following example demonstrates:
0              -> select biblio topics
               -> show format information
0              The following commands are provided by the $BIBLIO.TOPICS format:
0                                                - 21 -
1
-
         ADD               - Prompts for new element values, creates a new record.
         USING ACTIVE ADD  - Reads values from active file, creates a new record.
         MERGE topic       - Prompts for value changes, modifies specified record.
         DISPLAY topic     - Displays a specified record in standard display style.
0        The following commands provide general information about your data base:
0        SHOW ELEMENTS       - Shows the names of elements for your subfile.
         SHOW ELE DESC elem  - Describes a specified element in your subfile.
         ->
0      Each topics table record  contains a TOPIC element as the  key,  a RETAIN ele-
       ment,  and a POINTER element (which should not be disturbed).   Because of the
       simple structure of the  records in this subfile,  the ADD  and MERGE commands
       handle most of your needs.   The following example shows how to enter new top-
       ics into the table:
0        -> select biblio topics
         -> add
0        \TOPIC          physics
         \RETAIN         yes
         -> add
0        \TOPIC          chemistry
         \RETAIN         yes
         ->
0      Enter a value for RETAIN;  it can be  anything you choose but do not press the
       RETURN key as the only response.   For example, you could enter the word 'yes'
       or you could enter a null value by typing two backslash characters.  This will
       hold the topic record in the table until you enter a bibliographic record that
       uses the topic.
0      Never use the REMOVE command to remove a topic table record.   The topic table
       also serves as a topic index and if  you remove the table record you may throw
       away index pointers and create problems.  The proper way to get rid of a topic
       table record is to use the MERGE command to remove the value of the RETAIN el-
       ement,  and  then remove all references  to that topic from  the bibliographic
       data base.   If you follow this procedure,  then SPIRES will automatically get
       rid of the topic record for you.
0      The final example  in this section will  show how you can  put an alphabetical
       list of your topics into the active file  (where you can save it or print it).
       The sequence of commands to do this is:
0        -> select biblio topics
         -> set nolist
         -> for subfile
         +> in active show keys all
         +> endfor
-
                                           - 22 -
1
-
-
0                                              Section 3
+                                              Section 3
0                       FINDING, DISPLAYING, AND PRINTING BIBLIOGRAPHIC RECORDS
+                       FINDING, DISPLAYING, AND PRINTING BIBLIOGRAPHIC RECORDS
-            The commands described in Section 2 of this document dealt with single biblio-
             graphic records and were presented to assist with the building and maintenance
             of a bibliographic  data base.   This section describes how  to gather collec-
             tions of records whose element values meet some criteria that you specify, how
             to display those records at the terminal in the APA or IEEE styles, and how to
             obtain formatted printouts of the records on one of the high-speed printers.
-
0            3.1   A DESCRIPTION OF INDEX SEARCHING
+            3.1   A DESCRIPTION OF INDEX SEARCHING
+                  _ ___________ __ _____ _________
0            In SPIRES,  there are several methods for gathering together records that meet
             some criteria that  you specify.   The simplest  way is to search  the indexes
             that are automatically provided with your bibliographic subfile.   In describ-
             ing how indexes work,  it is useful to  draw an analogy between the records in
             your file and the books in a library.    Each book (a record)  in a library (a
             subfile)  sits on the shelves and can  be uniquely identified and retrieved by
             its call number (an ID number).  Libraries usually maintain author, title, and
             subject card catalogs (indexes) that you can search to obtain a list (a search
             result) of call numbers of books to inspect.  Stretching the analogy to make a
             point,  when a new book comes into a library,  it is placed on a special shelf
             until a librarian has a chance to create  new catalog cards for it and move it
             to the main shelves.
0            In SPIRES, new records (and ones that have been modified) are stored in a spe-
             cial area called the  deferred queue until shortly after midnight  when a pro-
             gram called SPIBILD  processes your file to  update the indexes for  those re-
             cords and move them to a permanent  storage area (called the tree).   The main
             point in all of this is that newly  added (or modified)  records cannot be re-
             trieved by searching indexes until SPIBILD has processed your file.  Note that
             if you have just added records and do  not want to wait for overnight process-
             ing,  you can process your file directly by following a procedure described in
             Section 4 of this document.
0            Assuming that you  have already selected your bibliographic  subfile,  you can
             ask to see the names of indexes by typing the following:
0              -> show indexes
               Goal Records:  REFERENCE
               Simple Index:  CLA, CLASS
               Simple Index:  AUT, AUTHOR, EDI, EDITOR
               Simple Index:  ORG, ORGANIZATION
               Simple Index:  TIT, TITLE
0                                                - 23 -
1
-        Simple Index:  DAT, DATE
         Simple Index:  TOP, TOPIC, TOPICS
         Simple Index:  KEY, KEYS, KEYWORD, KEYWORDS
0      Each line  represents an individual index  and shows the different  names that
       can be used to refer to the index.   Note that the names are the same as names
       of elements  in your subfile  and indicate  from which elements  those indexes
       were constructed.  For a description of any of these indexes, type the command
       SHOW INDEX DESC followed by the name of an index, as in the following example:
0        -> show index desc author
0        This index lets you retrieve records based on the names of authors
         and editors.  This index is organized as a personal-name index, and
         therefore offers some flexibility in the way you specify your search.
         For example, a reference with an author stored as DON KNUTH would be
         retrieved by the requests FIND AUTHOR DON KNUTH, FIND AUTHOR D KNUTH
         or FIND AUTHOR KNUTH.
0        -> sho index desc title
0        This index lets you retrieve records based on words in the title of
         the reference.  This index is organized as a word index, and will
         take all of the words in your search request and retrieve all
         records whose titles contain those words, regardless of their
         relative order.  For example, a reference with the title THE WIND IN
         THE WILLOWS would be retrieved by the request FIND TITLE WILLOWS WIND.
         ->
0      As you can see  from the above descriptions,  you search  indexes by using the
       FIND command.   You type the word FIND followed by the name of an index,  fol-
       lowed by a relational operator and a  value.   If you omit the operator,  then
       the equals (=)  operator is assumed.   It  is possible to join multiple search
       criteria with the logical connectors AND,  OR,   and AND NOT to construct com-
       pound requests,   and the  rules for doing  this are  described in  the Œ‡ƒ	Œ
       Œ„‰’ˆ „’ Ž„›’ˆ  manual.   SPIRES will perform your  search request and
       retrieve a collection of records known as  a search result.   For example,  to
       retrieve all records authored or edited by Don Knuth, you could type:
0        -> find author = knuth
         -Result: 1 REFERENCE
         ->
0      Similarly, to find all records with a topic value of 'test', you could type:
0        -> find topic = test
         -Result: 2 REFERENCES
         ->
-
-
0                                          - 24 -
1
-            3.2   DISPLAYING RECORDS WITH THE TYPE COMMAND
+            3.2   DISPLAYING RECORDS WITH THE TYPE COMMAND
+                  __________ _______ ____ ___ ____ _______
0            When you have obtained a search result,  you  can use the TYPE command to dis-
             play the selected records.  For example:
0              -> find topic test
               -Result: 2 REFERENCES
               -> type
0              \ID             1
               \CLASS          Book
               \AUTHOR(1)      D. E. Knuth
               \TITLE          Fundamental Algorithms
               \INSIDE         The Art of Computer Programming
               \VOLUME         I
               \DATE           1967
               \PUBLISHER      Addison-Wesley
               \TOPIC(1)       CS
               \TOPIC(2)       TEST
               \ENTERED        07/01/83
               \MODIFIED       07/01/83
0              \ID             2
               \CLASS          Article
               \AUTHOR(1)      Jeff Mapes
               \TITLE          Toads of the Western World
               \INSIDE         Toad Gazette
               \VOLUME         2
               \NUMBER         3
               \DATE           June 1983
               \TOPIC(1)       ANIMALS
               \TOPIC(2)       TEST
               \ENTERED        07/01/83
               \MODIFIED       07/01/83
               ->
0            Records are presented in the same format as they would appear with the DISPLAY
             command.   The TYPE command allows a number of useful options,  a few of which
             will be demonstrated here.   You can include a list of element names after the
             word TYPE to limit the display to only those elements.   Continuing our previ-
             ous example:
0              -> show result
               -Result: 2 REFERENCES
               -> type id author title
0              ID = 1;
               AUTHOR = D. E. Knuth;
               TITLE = Fundamental Algorithms;
0              ID = 2;
               AUTHOR = Jeff Mapes;
               TITLE = Toads of the Western World;
               ->
0                                                - 25 -
1
-
       SPIRES displays the reference elements in a  form known as the standard format
       when you include element names on the TYPE command.  Another option is to have
       the records displayed into  your active file by including the  words IN ACTIVE
       before the TYPE command.   Once the records  are in your active file,  you can
       type the PRINT command to get a quick printout.   A better way to get a nicely
       formatted printout of your records will be discussed later in this section.
-
0      3.3   DISPLAYING RECORDS IN APA AND IEEE STYLES
+      3.3   DISPLAYING RECORDS IN APA AND IEEE STYLES
+            __________ _______ __ ___ ___ ____ ______
0      One of the  advantages of storing bibliographic  records in a data  base is to
       provide some flexibility in the way records can be displayed.   The format set
       for your subfile allows  you to see records in an  approximation of either the
       standard APA or IEEE style.  To specify one of these styles, include the words
       USING APA or USING IEEE immediately in front of the TYPE (or DISPLAY) command,
       as shown in the following example:
0        -> find topic test
         -Result: 2 REFERENCES
         -> using apa type
0        [1]     Knuth, D. E. Fundamental Algorithms. In The Art of Computer
                 Programming. Addison-Wesley, 1967.
0                This is a standard reference for programmers.
0                Topics:  CS, TEST, COMPUTERS
0        [2]     Mapes, Jeff. Toads of the Western World. Toad Gazette, June
                 1983, 2(3).
0                Topics:  ANIMALS, TEST
0        -> using ieee type
0        [1]     Knuth, D. E., Fundamental Algorithms, Addison-Wesley, The Art
                 of Computer Programming, 1967.
0                This is a standard reference for programmers.
0                Topics:  CS, TEST, COMPUTERS
0        [2]     Mapes, Jeff, "Toads of the Western World," Toad Gazette,
                 Vol. 2, No. 3, June 1983.
0                Topics:  ANIMALS, TEST
         ->
0      In both examples,  the ID number is presented in brackets followed by the body
       of the reference, with abstract, comments,  and topic information presented on
-                                          - 26 -
1
-            additional lines.   Note that the USING prefixes  can be used with the DISPLAY
             command as well, so that you type USING APA DISPLAY 3 after adding record num-
             ber 3 to see how it looks in APA format.
-
0            3.4   PREPARING HIGH-QUALITY PRINTED OUTPUT
+            3.4   PREPARING HIGH-QUALITY PRINTED OUTPUT
+                  _________ ____________ _______ ______
0            Occasionally you  may want a  high-quality printout of  a selected set  of re-
             cords, possibly for inclusion in a paper or other document.   First,  obtain a
             search result (or stack) of desired records;  then,  sequence the selected re-
             cords in a  reasonable order and invoke  a special utility program  which will
             assist in preparing the records for printing.  The following sections describe
             the steps in this procedure.
-
0            3.4.1   Overview of the Printing Procedure
+            3.4.1   Overview of the Printing Procedure
+                    ________ __ ___ ________ _________
0            To select  the records to  print,  retrieve the  records with an  index search
             (keeping in  mind that new  records will not be  retrieved until your  file is
             processed).  Owners of bibliographic subfiles often store a specific code word
             in the topic  element of each reference  for a particular paper  so that those
             records can be easily retrieved.   To retrieve all records in your subfile (if
             your file has been processed),  type  the EXTRACT command.   Other methods for
             gathering records involve the STACK command and the use of Global For process-
             ing techniques,  and are covered in  the Œ‡ƒ	Œ Œ„‰’ˆ „’ Ž„›’ˆ manual,
             available in Document Sales, Forsythe Hall.
0            Once you have a result or stack of  records to print,  sort them by typing the
             command SEQUENCE SORTKEY.  SORTKEY is a special element of your subfile called
             a virtual element whose only function is to sort records that are to be print-
             ed in the APA or IEEE style.   Records are sorted by author, then by date, and
             then by title.   If you want to know  the exact sorting rules used by SORTKEY,
             you can type SHOW ELEMENT DESC SORTKEY.   Alternatively, to sort records by ID
             number,  type SEQUENCE  ID.   Note that the SEQUENCE command  can handle about
             2000 records at most.  If you are over this limit, you must use a more compli-
             cated program called SPISORT  to do the sorting.   The SPISORT  program is de-
             scribed in  the Œ‡ƒ	Œ ‰’„ †“›š  manual,  available in  Document Sales,
             Forsythe Hall.
0            When you have completed the sorting process,  you will have an ordered collec-
             tion of records called a stack.   The last step is to invoke a special utility
             known as a SPIRES  protocol to prepare the sorted records  for printing.   Two
             protocols,  named PRINT.APA and PRINT.IEEE are  made available to you when you
             use your bibliographic subfile.   Select the one  you want by typing the name,
             preceded by two periods (for example,  ..PRINT.APA).   These protocols let you
             select various options to control the appearance of the printed output.
-
-                                                - 27 -
1
-      3.4.2   Using the PRINT.APA and PRINT.IEEE Protocols
+      3.4.2   Using the PRINT.APA and PRINT.IEEE Protocols
+              _____ ___ _____ ___ ___ _____ ____ _________
0      The PRINT.APA and PRINT.IEEE  protocols are used to prepare a  sorted stack of
       bibliographic records for  printing.   Both protocols operate  in an identical
       fashion,  the only difference being the  style of output produced.   To invoke
       one of these protocols,  type two periods followed by the name of the protocol
       (i.e. ..PRINT.APA).  If you have not yet prepared a stack of records, the pro-
       tocol will remind you what you must do and will not allow you to proceed.
0      If a stack has  been properly prepared,  the protocol indicates  the number of
       records it will process, lists the current values of seven different print op-
       tion settings, displays a SETTING? prompt, and waits for a response.   At this
       prompt,  you can type  a question mark to see the  following list of available
       responses:
0        Type ? to see the names and values of current settings.
         Type GO to accept current settings and do the printing.
         Type a setting name for a description of that setting.
         Type a setting name followed by a value to change that setting.
         Type RESET to reset settings to their initial values.
         Press the BREAK key to cancel the entire print request.
0      The following  table provides  a description  of each  of the  seven available
       print option settings:
0      HEADER      The HEADER  setting controls which text  string will be used  as a
                   title header on the first page  of the printed bibliography.   The
                   header line will  be centered between the columns  defined as LEFT
                   and RIGHT by  the COLUMNS setting option.   The  default header is
                   'REFERENCES'.   If  you type  the word HEADER  followed by  a text
                   string,  then that string becomes the new header.   Note that your
                   new header value  may be in upper and lower  case characters.   If
                   you do not want a header line, then type HEADER NONE.
0      NUMBERS     The NUMBERS setting  controls the manner in  which references will
                   be numbered  in the output.    Three values are  recognized.   The
                   SEQUENTIAL value will cause references to be numbered sequentially
                   starting at 1,  and will place  a decimal point after each number.
                   The ID value will cause the ID number of each reference to be dis-
                   played,  enclosed in square brackets.    The UNNUMBERED value will
                   suppress the display of numbers for references.  The default is to
                   generate numbers sequentially.
0      EMPHASIS    The EMPHASIS setting controls the manner in which titles (and vol-
                   ume numbers)  will be emphasized in  the output.   Four values are
                   recognized.   The UNDERLINE  value will cause titles  to be under-
                   lined.  The ITALICS value will cause titles to be printed using an
                   italic character set.  The CAPS value will cause titles to be cap-
                   italized.   The NORMAL value will cause titles to be printed with-
                   out emphasis.  The default is to underline titles.   Note that the
                   ITALICS value can  only be used if  you print on the  3800 or 9700
                   printers,  and that a print option indicating two 12-pitch charac-
                   ter sets will be supplied automatically.
-                                          - 28 -
1
-            COLUMNS     The COLUMNS  setting controls the  alignment of each  reference on
                         the printed page.   The value consists of four numbers,  separated
                         by commas,  which  are interpreted in the  following manner:   The
                         first number (nstart) indicates the column in which the number for
                         a reference begins,  and must be in  the range from 1 to 21.   The
                         second number (start)   indicates the column in which  the body of
                         the reference begins, and must be in the range from 1 to 31.   The
                         third number (left) indicates the column to be used as a left mar-
                         gin for  subsequent lines of  the reference,   and must be  in the
                         range from 1 to 31.   The fourth number (right) indicates the col-
                         umn to be used as a right  margin for subsequent lines of the ref-
                         erence, and must be in the range from 40 to 120.  The default val-
                         ue (13,20,20,90)   is appropriate for  printing references  with a
                         12-pitch character set,  leaving one inch  margins on the left and
                         right sides of the page.   Note that if you adjust the column val-
                         ues for  printing at  10-pitch,  you  must also  adjust the  print
                         OPTION values to select appropriate 10-pitch character sets.
0            INCLUDE     The  INCLUDE setting  controls which  of  the annotation  elements
                         (ABSTRACT, COMMENTS and TOPICS)  should be included in the output.
                         To change  the setting you type  the word INCLUDE followed  by the
                         names of elements to include, separated by commas.  You may abbre-
                         viate any  element name to  three characters.   For  example,  you
                         could type INCLUDE ABS,TOP to include abstract and topics informa-
                         tion (and exclude comments).   The special values ALL and NONE can
                         be used to  include or exclude all annotation  elements.   The de-
                         fault is NONE.    Note that the text of the  ABSTRACT element will
                         appear after the main body of  the reference and will be reformat-
                         ted into  a single  paragraph,  and aligned  between the  left and
                         right margins as defined in the COLUMNS setting.   The text of the
                         COMMENTS element will appear next,   again formatted into a single
                         paragraph.  Finally the list of topic words will be presented on a
                         single line, separated by commas.  Note that it is possible to ar-
                         range for long sections of abstract  or comments text to be broken
                         into multiple paragraphs  by including null element  values at the
                         places in a record where you  want paragraph breaks (see Section 2
                         for details about entering null values).
0            AUTORUN     The AUTORUN setting controls whether or  not the print job created
                         by this  utility should be  automatically submitted when  you type
                         the GO command.  The default value is ON.   If you want the print-
                         ready dataset to be retained in your active file when this utility
                         completes,  then type AUTORUN OFF.   You  will then be able to in-
                         spect the dataset,  save it permanently if you wish,  and print it
                         explicitly with the PRINT command.
0            OPTIONS     The OPTIONS setting  allows you to override the  default print op-
                         tions that indicate which printer, forms,  and character sets will
                         be used  for the  output.   If  you do  not explicitly  change the
                         OPTIONS setting,  then  suitable print options will  be calculated
                         based on your  other selected settings.   If you  override the de-
                         fault, you must make sure that the options you specify are consis-
                         tant with your other settings.  For example, if EMPHASIS is set to
-                                                - 29 -
1
-                  ITALICS and you are overriding the default print options, then you
                   must specify  both a  normal and  an italic  character set  in the
                   CHARS option.   If you specify FORMS 1181 or 9511,  you must indi-
                   cate a character set valid for  the 3800 printer.   If you specify
                   FORMS BOND or  3HOL,  you must indicate a character  set valid for
                   the 9700 printer.   Also be aware that the default COLUMNS setting
                   values are  intended for  use with  a 12-pitch  character set  (12
                   characters per inch).
-      Following is an example that demonstrates  the complete process of retrieving,
       sequencing and printing a set of records:
0        -> select biblio
         -> find topic test
         -Result: 2 REFERENCES
         -> sequence sortkey
         -Stack: 2 REFERENCES
         -> ..print.apa
0        Two  references will be printed in the APA style with these
         settings:
0        Setting   Current-Value                 Alternatives
+        _______   _____________                 ____________
0        Numbers   SEQuential                    (ID,UNNumbered)
         Emphasis  UNDerline                     (ITAlics,CAPs,NORmal)
         Columns   13,20,20,90                   <nstart,start,left,right>
         Include   NONe                          (ALL,ABStract,COMments,TOPics)
         Autorun   ON                            (OFF)
         Header    REFERENCES
         Options   UNN CC FORMS=BOND CHARS=CU12
0        Setting (press RETURN for help)?
0        Type ? to see the names and values of current settings.
         Type GO to accept current settings and do the printing.
         Type a setting name for a description of that setting.
         Type a setting name followed by a value to change that setting.
         Type RESET to reset settings to their initial values.
         Press the BREAK key to cancel the entire print request.
0        Setting (press RETURN for help)?  header Bibliography
         Header is now Bibliography
0        Setting (press RETURN for help)?  include topics
         Include is now TOPics.
0        Setting (press RETURN for help)?  go
0        JOB 1814 BIBLIO AWAITING PRINT PRIO=9  POS=28 FORMS=BOND  LINES=22
         ->
-
                                           - 30 -
1
-            You  should  be aware  that  the  printing  procedure,  described  above,   is
             considerably more expensive  than the standard procedure of  searching for and
             displaying records,  in  terms of CPU time.    If you are planning  to print a
             large bibliography,  you are advised to  run this procedure during the evening
             or on a weekend to minimize your costs.    Also,  if you are planning to print
             the same collection of records several times,   you can run the procedure with
             AUTORUN OFF and then save the resulting  print-ready dataset in a WYLBUR file.
             You can then print the bibliography at  any time using the PRINT FROM command,
             thus avoiding the expense of rerunning the print procedure.
-
0            3.4.3   A Quick Method for Specifying a Print Request
+            3.4.3   A Quick Method for Specifying a Print Request
+                    _ _____ ______ ___ __________ _ _____ _______
0            If you know all of the settings you wish to use in requesting a printout,  you
             can avoid being prompted  for the information by including a  list of settings
             and values directly on the PRINT.APA  or PRINT.IEEE command.   The information
             you enter is the same as that supplied at the SETTING?  prompts,  and you must
             separate the individual  responses with backslash characters.    For instance,
             the previous example could have been entered on a single line in the following
             way:
0              -> ..print.apa header Bibliography\include topics\go
0              JOB 1814 BIBLIO AWAITING PRINT PRIO=9  POS=28 FORMS=BOND  LINES=22
               ->
0            If you make an error in one of your specifications, then the print utility ac-
             cepts all  valid specifications already received  and begins prompting  at the
             point that the error was detected.
0            As another  example,  suppose  you experiment  with different  combinations of
             print settings and  decide that you prefer a particular  combination that for-
             mats the  output for a  10-pitch character set.    The command for  doing this
             would be:
0              -> ..print.apa col 11,15,15,75\opt UNN CC FORMS=BOND CHARS=CU10\go
-
