0                                              Section 4
+                                              Section 4
0                          CREATING AND CUSTOMIZING A BIBLIOGRAPHIC DATA BASE
+                          CREATING AND CUSTOMIZING A BIBLIOGRAPHIC DATA BASE
-            This section  describes the procedures for  creating a new  bibliographic data
             base and for customizing the definition of the data base to suit your particu-
             lar needs.  The customization procedures are necessary if you expect to extend
             the ability to add records and search  for records to other accounts.   All of
             the customization procedures discussed are general techniques that can be per-
             formed by the owner  of any SPIRES file,  and are discussed  in more detail in
             the Œ‡ƒ	Œ  €’›“’ manual, available in Document Sales, Forsythe Hall.
-
0            4.1   CREATING A BIBLIOGRAPHIC DATA BASE
+            4.1   CREATING A BIBLIOGRAPHIC DATA BASE
+                  ________ _ _____________ ____ ____
0            If you  decide that  the bibliographic  system described  in this  document is
             suitable for your needs, you can type a single command to invoke a WYLBUR exec
             file utility  that asks questions  and creates a  private SPIRES data  base on
             your account.  This setup utility is self-explanatory, so let's run through an
             example and then  make additional comments.   To  create the data base  that I
             have been using for demonstration purposes in this document,  I typed the fol-
             lowing command:
0              > exec from lib#biblio public
0              #BIBLIO Exec File
0              This utility asks you a series of simple questions, and builds a SPIRES
               data base to hold bibliographic references based on your answers.  You
               should obtain a copy of the document titled "Managing Bibliographic
               References Using a SPIRES Data Base" before running this setup utility.
               This document can be purchased at Document Sales in Forsythe Hall, or
               printed by typing the command PRINT FROM DOC#BIBLIO PUBLIC.  To get out
               of this utility without building a data base, press the BREAK or ATTN
               key in response to any prompt.
0              This setup utility needs to use your active file as a temporary working
               area, but there is already something in it.  Please answer YES if it is
               safe to dispose of what is there or NO to return to WYLBUR where you
               can inspect and save the contents.
0              OK to clear the active file (Yes/No)? YES
0              Please provide a subfile name for your SPIRES data base.  This is the
               name that you will use whenever you want to work with your data base.
               The name should be reasonably short but descriptive, and may be several
0                                                - 33 -
1
-        words in length.  Avoid using punctuation in the name and choose a name
         different from other data bases that you already own.  Examples of
         subfile names are MEDREFS and SOLAR BIBLIO.
0        Subfile Name?  BIBLIO
0        Your subfile will be named BIBLIO
0        Is this the name you want (Yes/No)? YES
0        Do you want a special keywords index constructed for your data base?  If
         you answer YES, then an index will be built from individual words from
         the TITLE, TOPIC, NOTE, ABSTRACT, and COMMENTS elements of your file,
         allowing you to easily search for text words without having to remember
         the specific details of where they were stored.  If you plan to annotate
         your references by using the ABSTRACT and COMMENTS elements, and expect
         to perform frequent searches based on that information, then you should
         answer YES to create the index.  Otherwise, answer NO and your disk
         storage charges will be reduced by some modest ammount.  If you decide
         not to build the index now, you can always change your mind and build it
         later using some special procedures.
0        OK to build KEYWORDS index (Yes/No)? YES
0        Do you require that all topic words and phrases, used to categorize
         references by topic area, be predefined in a special topics table
         associated with your data base?  If you answer YES, then only topic
         words that have been predefined will be accepted when entering
         bibliographic records.  If you answer NO, then any words or phrases
         that are entered will be accepted as valid topics.
0        Require topics to be predefined (Yes/No)? YES
0        Would you like like a printed copy of the SPIRES file definition that
         is generated by this setup utility?  This printout provides a formal
         description of the structure of your bibliographic data base and is
         useful to have if you plan to do any further customization of your
         file, as described in the document for this system.  After answering
         this prompt, please wait for a few moments while your data base is
         being generated.
0        Print the generated file definition (Yes/No)? YES
0        JOB 4193 FILEDEF  AWAITING PRINT PRIO=9  POS=2  FORMS=1181  LINES=481
0        -File definition compiled
0        This setup utility has now completed its attempt to generate a
         bibliographic data base according to your specifications.  If all went
         well, you should be able to select your new SPIRES subfile and begin
         adding records by using one of the techniques described in the document
         titled "Managing Bibliographic References Using a SPIRES Data Base".
         ->
-                                          - 34 -
1
-
             This example demonstrated the complete process of creating a new bibliographic
             data base.    To begin the  creation process,   you type EXEC  FROM LIB#BIBLIO
             PUBLIC.   This  starts up a WYLBUR  exec file which  asks you to respond  to a
             short series of questions.   In my example,  I had some information in the ac-
             tive file when I began, and the utility first asked if it could erase that in-
             formation before proceeding.  The utility then asked for a subfile name, and I
             decided to  call my subfile  BIBLIO (thereby  causing BIBLIO CODES  and BIBLIO
             TOPICS subfiles to be generated as well).   After confirming the subfile name,
             I requested that a  KEYWORDS index be included in my  file,  and required that
             topic words  be predefined in  a table before they  can be used  to categorize
             references.   Finally, I asked for a printed copy of the file definition to be
             generated.
0            The setup  utility then compiled my  file definition,  creating a  new (empty)
             SPIRES file,   and displayed the  message '-File definition  compiled'.   This
             should be the only message that the  SPIRES compiler produces.   If error mes-
             sages appear at this point,  then you probably already have a SPIRES file with
             the same name  as the one you are  trying to create.   Run  the utility again,
             choosing a different subfile name.
0            When you have successfully  generated a file,  you can proceed  to select your
             new subfiles and try adding records, using the techniques described in Section
             2 of this document.   If you require topics  to be predefined,  then add a few
             topics to the topic table before adding bibliographic records.
-
0            4.2   SPECIAL COMMANDS AVAILABLE TO FILE OWNERS
+            4.2   SPECIAL COMMANDS AVAILABLE TO FILE OWNERS
+                  _______ ________ _________ __ ____ ______
0            The name you provide in the setup utility  is the name that you (or anyone you
             extend privileges to)  will use to access the bibliographic data base.   There
             are a number of  operations that the file owner may need  to perform which re-
             quire the manipulation of the file definition  itself.   To do this,  the file
             owner must  know the name of  the file (which is  not the same as  the subfile
             name).   The setup  utility constructs the file name by  joining with periods,
             your account,  the special word BIBLIO,  and the first seven characters of the
             first word of your subfile name.   In the setup example above,  if the account
             was GA.JSM, then the full name of the file would be GA.JSM.BIBLIO.BIBLIO.   If
             the subfile name was REFERENCES, the file name would be GA.JSM.BIBLIO.REFEREN,
             or if  the subfile  name was  MEDICAL ABSTRACTS  then the  file name  would be
             GA.JSM.BIBLIO.MEDICAL.   If you know the name of a subfile,  you can determine
             the file name in the following manner:
0              -> select biblio
               -> show eval $filename
               GA.JSM.BIBLIO.BIBLIO
               ->
0            Once you know the name of your SPIRES  file you can perform several useful op-
             erations, such as printing a copy of your file definition, modifying your file
             definition to allow other accounts to access your data base,  and erasing your
-                                                - 35 -
1
-      data  base when  you  no longer  need  it.   Before  you  customize your  file
       definition, it is recommended that you first print a copy of the original file
       definition for reference, as in the following example for account GA.JSM:
0        -> select filedef
         -> perform print ga.jsm.biblio.biblio
         JOB 4913 GAJ#FILE AWAITING PRINT 9  F=1181  L=485
         ->
-
-      4.2.1   Processing a Bibliographic File Online
+      4.2.1   Processing a Bibliographic File Online
+              __________ _ _____________ ____ ______
0      In Section 3,  the fact was mentioned  that newly added (or modified)  biblio-
       graphic records  cannot be retrieved by  searching indexes until your  file is
       processed.   Shortly after midnight each night, a program called SPIBILD auto-
       matically does  this processing by making  all recent additions  and modifica-
       tions permanent and bringing all indexes  up to date.   Occasionally,  a situ-
       ation may  arise where  it is  inconvenient to  wait for  overnight processing
       before retrieving new records.   In this case,  you can process the file your-
       self at the terminal,  as is demonstrated by the following example for account
       GA.JSM:
0        -> call spibild
         -Welcome to SPIBILD
         -? process ga.jsm.biblio.biblio
         -Passing:       2 records of record-type 01
         -Processed:     2 DEFQ records of record-type 01
         -Compute time:     .137 seconds
         -Elapsed time:    2.840 seconds
         -Core usage: 0091/0484
         -?
0      In the above example, I first entered the SPIBILD processing environment,  and
       then typed the command  PROCESS followed by the name of  my bibliographic file
       (not the subfile name).   SPIBILD moved the new records into my data base, up-
       dated the indexes, and reported how much time and space was used.  If I wanted
       to, I could then return to SPIRES, select my subfile,  and perform the desired
       search.
-
0      4.2.2   Adding Multiple Records in a Single Operation
+      4.2.2   Adding Multiple Records in a Single Operation
+              ______ ________ _______ __ _ ______ _________
0      In Section 2,  a procedure was described which let you collect the information
       for a single bibliographic record in your WYLBUR active file and then add that
       record to the data base with the USING ACTIVE ADD command.   It is also possi-
       ble to collect many  records in the active file and then have  them added in a
       single operation,  but the procedure  is somewhat different.   When collecting
       the records,  you  must make sure that  individual records are separated  by a
-                                          - 36 -
1
-            single  line that  contains  two backslash  characters  (\\).   The  following
             example shows how to prepare and enter records using this procedure.
0              -> collect clear
                   1. >  \class article
                   2. >  \author Adele Goldberg
                   3. >  \title Introducing the Smalltalk-80 System
                   4. >  \inside BYTE
                   5. >  \date August 1981
                   6. >  \\
                   7. >  \class aarticle
                   8. >  \author Daniel Ingalls
                   9. >  \title Design Principles Behind Smalltalk
                  10. >  \inside BYTE
                  11. >  \date August 1981
                  12. >  \\
                  13. >  \class article
                  14. >  \author Glenn Krasner
                  15. >  \title The Smalltalk-80 Virtual Machine
                  16. >  \inside BYTE
                  17. >  \date August 1981
                  18. >  ***                    <BREAK key pressed>
               -> call spibild
               -Welcome to SPIBILD
               -? set exception badrecs
               -? set format $biblio.batch
               -? batch biblio
               -Processing file: GA.JSM.BIBLIO
               -Compute time:     .120 seconds
               -Elapsed time:    1.873 seconds
               -Core usage: 0049/0251
               - ADD     1,     1  @Line      6.     Key = 4
               -Element=CLASS: Input Error:    CLASS must be either A,B,R,T,D,M,C,I or O.
               -Serious data error, code=E46
               -Error at or before line       8.
               -FORMAT execution error, code=S847
               -Error at or before line      12.
               -*ADD     2,     1  @Line     12.
               - ADD     3,     2  @Line      1.     Key = 5
               -Passing:       2 records of record-type 01
               -   Requests/Success:
                ADD       3       2
                SUM       3       2
               -End of BATCH/BUILD
               -Compute time:     .202 seconds
               -Elapsed time:    1.974 seconds
               -Core usage: 0148/0254
               -?
0            In the above example, I first prepared three records in the active file, sepa-
             rated by lines containing two backslash characters.  Then I got out of collect
             mode and entered the SPIBILD processing environment.  Before attempting to add
             the records,  I typed the command SET  EXCEPTION BADRECS (where BADRECS was an
-                                                - 37 -
1
-      arbitrary  ORVYL file  name  that I  chose).   This  command  is not  strictly
       necessary,  but provides a convenient way of isolating those records that fail
       to add due to errors, as we will see.  Finally I typed the BATCH command, fol-
       lowed by the name  of the bibliographic subfile.   The rest  of the lines from
       the example are messages from SPIBILD describing what happened.
0      SPIBILD first processed the file, and then started adding records.   The first
       record was added sucessfully and was assigned  an ID number of 4.   The second
       record had  an error,   and SPIBILD displayed  error messages  indicating that
       there was an invalid  value for the class element before line  8 of the active
       file.   The third record was added successfully  and was assigned an ID number
       of 5.   SPIBILD then displayed some  summary information indicating that three
       adds had been attempted, and that only two were successful.
0      The purpose of setting an exception file  was to enable SPIBILD to isolate all
       of the records that failed to add, and so we can continue the previous example
       in the following way:
0        -? get badrecs clear
         -? list
             7.     \class aarticle
             8.     \author Daniel Ingalls
             9.     \title Design Principles Behind Smalltalk
            10.     \inside BYTE
            11.     \date August 1981
            12.     \\
         -? change 'aa' to 'a'
             7.     \class article
         -? set exception badrecs
         Replace BADRECS ? yes
         -? set format $biblio.batch
         -? batch biblio
         - ADD     1,     1  @Line     12.     Key = 6
         -Passing:       1 records of record-type 01
         -   Requests/Success:
          ADD       1       1
          SUM       1       1
         -End of BATCH/BUILD
         -Compute time:     .224 seconds
         -Elapsed time:    2.704 seconds
         -Core usage: 0148/0260
         -? erase badrecs
         BADRECS erased in ORVYL File System
         -?
0      To bring the records that had errors into the active file, I typed the command
       GET BADRECS CLEAR.   I then listed the active file, identified the error,  and
       used a WYLBUR editing command to fix the erroneous line.   After resetting the
       exception file and the format,  I typed  the BATCH command,  and the remaining
       record was added succesfully and was assigned an ID number of 6.  Since all my
       records had been sucessfully added,  I  erased the exception file (to minimize
       my disk storage charges).
-
                                           - 38 -
1
-            A few concluding  remarks should be offered  here.   Some people who  use this
             method of entering records like to type  the command SET TERMINAL HEIGHT 0 be-
             fore they begin,  to avoid having to press  the RETURN key every time that the
             screen fills up with messages.   Adding  records in the manner described above
             also causes your file to be processed, so you can immediately CALL SPIRES, se-
             lect your subfile, and do index searches.  The cost of this method is slightly
             more expensive than entering a record at a time in SPIRES during the day,  but
             can be significantly less  expensive if you do it in the  evenings or on week-
             ends.   Also,  because the preparation of records is reduced to a text editing
             task,  a large bibliographic data base could be prepared on a microcomputer or
             word processor,  transferred to the IBM 3081 machine,  and entered in a single
             operation,  thus minimizing  the online connect charges for  building the data
             base.   Similarly, people wishing to move a bibliographic data base on another
             computer to the data base described in  this document should arrange to format
             their records in the manner described above, and then transfer them to the IBM
             3081,  either by a direct connection or via magnetic tape.   Those who wish to
             know more about SPIBILD and the BATCH  and PROCESS commands should consult the
             Œ‡ƒ	Œ Œ„‰’ˆ „’ Ž„›’ˆ manual,   available in Document Sales,  Forsythe
             Hall, for further information.
-
0            4.2.3   Destroying a Bibliographic Data Base
+            4.2.3   Destroying a Bibliographic Data Base
+                    __________ _ _____________ ____ ____
0            If you decide that you want to get rid  of all traces of your file (and reduce
             your disk storage charges), then you can use the following procedure:
0              -> zap file ga.jsm.biblio.biblio
               -Do you want to destroy file 'GA.JSM.BIBLIO.BIBLIO'?  yes
               -> select filedef
               -> remove ga.jsm.biblio.biblio
               ->
0            This procedure throws  away the actual physical  file,  all of the  records in
             that file,  and the record in the FILEDEF subfile that describes the structure
             of the data base.
-
0            4.3   CUSTOMIZING THE FILE DEFINITION
+            4.3   CUSTOMIZING THE FILE DEFINITION
+                  ___________ ___ ____ __________
0            There are several  different ways in which  the owner of a  bibliographic file
             can customize the definition of that file.  The most common reason for custom-
             izing a file is  to extend to other accounts the ability to  add records or to
             search for and display records,  although  several other modifications are de-
             scribed as well.  Whenever a new SPIRES data base is defined, a special record
             describing the characteristics of the file is added to a system subfile called
             FILEDEF.   A section of that definition, called the subfile section, describes
             the privileges and restrictions associated with each subfile in the data base.
             We will concentrate on understanding and modifying this part of the file defi-
             nition.
-                                                - 39 -
1
-      To work with  the file definition,  select the FILEDEF  subfile,  TRANSFER the
       record for your file into the active file,  and use WYLBUR editing commands to
       list and  modify the definition.   When  you are satisfied with  the modifica-
       tions, use the UPDATE command to save the new definition.   You must then wait
       until the file is processed by SPIBILD (around midnight each night) before the
       changes take effect.   The following example  shows how to inspect the subfile
       section for the file defined earlier in this section:
0        -> set nolist
         -> select filedef
         -> transfer ga.jsm.biblio.biblio
         -> list 'SUBFILE'
            453.  SUBFILE-NAME = BIBLIO;
            465.  SUBFILE-NAME = BIBLIO CODES;
            473.  SUBFILE-NAME = BIBLIO TOPICS;
         -> list 453/last
            453.  SUBFILE-NAME = BIBLIO;
            454.    EXP = This is a subfile of annotated bibliographic references.;
            455.    GOAL-RECORD = REC01;
            456.      ACCOUNTS = GA.JSM;
            457.        SECURE-SWITCHES = 1, 2;
            458.        NOSEARCH = 2;
            459.        SELECT-COMMAND = !SET NOECHO NOSTOP;
            460.        SELECT-COMMAND = SET COMPXEQ + BIBLIO PROTOCOLS;
            461.        SELECT-COMMAND = XEQ FROM BIBLIO.MESSAGE;
            462.        SELECT-COMMAND = SET FORMAT $BIBLIO;
            463.        SELECT-COMMAND = SET STOP;
            464.      COMMENTS = Topics must be predefined in Topics table;
            465.  SUBFILE-NAME = BIBLIO CODES;
            466.    EXP = This is a table of journal abbreviation codes and names,;
            467.    EXP = and is part of a data base of bibliographic references.;
            468.    GOAL-RECORD = REC02;
            469.      ACCOUNTS = GA.JSM;
            470.        FORMAT = $BIBLIO.CODES;
            471.  SUBFILE-NAME = BIBLIO TOPICS;
            472.    EXP = This is a table of user-defined topic words and phrases,;
            473.    EXP = and is part of a data base of bibliographic references.;
            474.    GOAL-RECORD = REC03;
            475.      ACCOUNTS = GA.JSM;
            476.        FORMAT = $BIBLIO.TOPICS;
0      The subfile  section of  the file  definition is  divided into  three separate
       parts,  one for each subfile in the  file.   Each section contains a series of
       element name and value assignment statements,  and each statement must be ter-
       minated with a  semicolon.   By changing the  values of these elements  and by
       adding or removing various statements,  you  can change several of the charac-
       teristics of the subfiles.
-
-
-                                          - 40 -
1
-            4.3.1   Changing Subfile Names
+            4.3.1   Changing Subfile Names
+                    ________ _______ _____
0            The SUBFILE-NAME element defines the name that will be used in order to select
             a particular subfile.    The subfile-names from the example  above are BIBLIO,
             BIBLIO CODES,  and BIBLIO TOPICS.   You can  easily change the names of any of
             your subfiles by giving new values to these elements.   Note that SPIRES asso-
             ciates the  name of  a subfile with  the physical  description of  the subfile
             through the GOAL-RECORD element.   The goal  record called REC01 always refers
             to the main bibliographic record, REC02 is the journal codes table,  and REC03
             is the topics table.   If you change subfile-name values,  be sure to end your
             new value with semicolons,   and remember that after you type  UPDATE you will
             have to wait until the next day for the new names to be recognized.
-
0            4.3.2   Changing Subfile Explanations
+            4.3.2   Changing Subfile Explanations
+                    ________ _______ ____________
0            The EXP element allows you to provide  a description of the contents and usage
             of any of your subfiles.   Typically, each value is a single line of text end-
             ing with a semicolon,   and there may be multiple lines  for each defined sub-
             file.   Any  account that has  permission to access  one of your  subfiles and
             knows the subfile name,   can type EXPLAIN SF followed by  the subfile name to
             read the explanation that you have provided.    If you are planning to allow a
             large number of accounts  to access your subfile,  take care  to write a clear
             and helpful subfile explanation.   Note  that simple default explanations have
             already been provided.
-
0            4.3.3   Changing Topic Restrictions
+            4.3.3   Changing Topic Restrictions
+                    ________ _____ ____________
0            In the setup procedure to build your data  base,  you are asked if you require
             topics to be predefined  in a topics table before being  used in bibliographic
             records.  If you answer YES to this question, the element assignment statement
             'SECURE-SWITCHES = 1,2;'  is placed into the subfile section  for your biblio-
             graphic subfile (see line 457 of the above example).   If you subsequently de-
             cide that you do not want the restriction,   you can remove this line from the
             subfile section.   Alternatively, if you decide that you want the restriction,
             you can insert this line into the subfile section.
-
0            4.3.4   Changing Default Prompting Settings
+            4.3.4   Changing Default Prompting Settings
+                    ________ _______ _________ ________
0            The subfile section of your bibliographic subfile has a sequence of assignment
             statements for an element called SELECT-COMMAND.  These lines contain commands
             that are  automatically executed whenever  you select your  bibliographic sub-
             file.   The line that  we will discuss here is the  one containing the command
             SET FORMAT $BIBLIO.   This line sets the format that provides all of the func-
             tions described in Section 2 of this document.  In Section 2, you learned that
-                                                - 41 -
1
-      the ADD and MERGE commands allow you to  be prompted at the terminal to add or
       modify bibliographic records,  and you also learned that you can control which
       elements are presented with the SET FORMAT * command.   If you want a specific
       set of elements to  be included for ADD or MERGE prompting  when you first se-
       lect your subfile,   modify the SELECT-COMMAND line in the  subfile section to
       include an element selection specification (see  Section 2.1.4).   As an exam-
       ple,  suppose you expect to enter references to articles and expect to provide
       topic words and lines of abstract text.  You could modify the line of the file
       definition as follows:
0        -> modify 462
            462.   SELECT-COMMAND = SET FORMAT $BIBLIO;
            Mods >                                    r art + top abs;
            462.   SELECT-COMMAND = SET FORMAT $BIBLIO art + top abs;
            Mods >
         ->
-
0      4.3.5   Giving Full Privileges to Other Accounts
+      4.3.5   Giving Full Privileges to Other Accounts
+              ______ ____ __________ __ _____ ________
0      Within each of the three subfile sections  is an element called ACCOUNTS which
       lists the accounts that have been given  full privileges for using the associ-
       ated subfile.  Accounts with full privileges may add, modify, search for, dis-
       play,  and remove records in a subfile.    The bibliographic data base is ini-
       tially created so that only the owner of the file has full privileges, and you
       should always keep  the owner's account number  as a value of  these elements.
       You may  extend full privileges  for any of your  three subfiles to  other ac-
       counts by appending additional account numbers,   separated by commas,  to the
       existing account.   For example,  if you wanted  to let both GA.XXX and GA.YYY
       add bibliographic records,  but  only let GA.XXX add new topics  to the table,
       you could modify the file definition as follows:
0        -> modify 456 475
            456.      ACCOUNTS = GA.JSM;
            Mods >                     r, ga.xxx, ga.yyy;
            475.      ACCOUNTS = GA.JSM, ga.xxx, ga.yyy;
            Mods >
            475.      ACCOUNTS = GA.JSM;
            Mods >                     r, ga.xxx;
            475.      ACCOUNTS = GA.JSM, ga.xxx;
            Mods >
         ->
0      Remember that the above changes only modify the copy of the file definition in
       the active file, and you must type UPDATE and then wait until the next day for
       the changes to become effective.
-
-
0                                          - 42 -
1
-            4.3.6   Giving Restricted Privileges to Other Accounts
+            4.3.6   Giving Restricted Privileges to Other Accounts
+                    ______ __________ __________ __ _____ ________
0            A data base  owner may wish to give  certain accounts the ability  to select a
             subfile and search for and display  records without allowing those accounts to
             add or modify records.  To do this, the file owner must first create an exten-
             sion to the subfile  section,  and then must include the  list of accounts and
             the statement that imposes the restriction into this new section.   Adding the
             statement,  'SECURE-SWITCHES = 3;' to the  new section will keep accounts from
             changing the contents of  records.   If the list of accounts  that you plan to
             enter is very long,  you may find some advantage in using one of the following
             special forms of the account:
0            GG....      This form would represent all accounts in group GG.
0            G.....      This form would  represent all accounts whose group  begins with G
                         (like GA, GX, and GG).
0            PUBLIC      This form represents every account on the machine.
0            As an example, suppose you want to modify your file definition to allow anyone
             to search and display records in  your subfile.   The following commands would
             perform the necessary modifications:
0              -> copy 455/464 to 464.1
               Line 464.55 is the last line.
               -> list 464.1/464.55
                  464.1   GOAL-RECORD = REC01;
                  464.15    ACCOUNTS = GA.JSM;
                  464.2       SECURE-SWITCHES = 1, 2;
                  464.25      NOSEARCH = 2;
                  464.3       SELECT-COMMAND = !SET NOECHO NOSTOP;
                  464.35      SELECT-COMMAND = SET COMPXEQ + BIBLIO PROTOCOLS;
                  464.4       SELECT-COMMAND = XEQ FROM BIBLIO.MESSAGE;
                  464.45      SELECT-COMMAND = SET FORMAT $BIBLIO;
                  464.5       SELECT-COMMAND = SET STOP;
                  464.55    COMMENTS = Topics must be predefined in Topics table;
               -> modify 464.15
                  464.15    ACCOUNTS = GA.JSM;
                  Mods >               rpublic;
                  464.15    ACCOUNTS = public;
                  Mods >
               -> insert 464.21
                  464.21      secure-switches = 3;
               -> list 453/464.55
                  453.  SUBFILE-NAME = BIBLIO;
                  454.    EXP = This is a subfile of annotated bibliographic references.;
                  455.    GOAL-RECORD = REC01;
                  456.      ACCOUNTS = GA.JSM;
                  457.        SECURE-SWITCHES = 1, 2;
                  458.        NOSEARCH = 2;
                  459.        SELECT-COMMAND = !SET NOECHO NOSTOP;
                  460.        SELECT-COMMAND = SET COMPXEQ + BIBLIO PROTOCOLS;
                  461.        SELECT-COMMAND = XEQ FROM BIBLIO.MESSAGE;
                  462.        SELECT-COMMAND = SET FORMAT $BIBLIO;
0                                                - 43 -
1
-           463.        SELECT-COMMAND = SET STOP;
            464.      COMMENTS = Topics must be predefined in Topics table;
            464.1   GOAL-RECORD = REC01;
            464.15    ACCOUNTS = public;
            464.2       SECURE-SWITCHES = 1, 2;
            464.21      secure-switches = 3;
            464.25      NOSEARCH = 2;
            464.3       SELECT-COMMAND = !SET NOECHO NOSTOP;
            464.35      SELECT-COMMAND = SET COMPXEQ + BIBLIO PROTOCOLS;
            464.4       SELECT-COMMAND = XEQ FROM BIBLIO.MESSAGE;
            464.45      SELECT-COMMAND = SET FORMAT $BIBLIO;
            464.5       SELECT-COMMAND = SET STOP;
            464.55    COMMENTS = Topics must be predefined in Topics table;
         ->
0      Now the subfile section for BIBLIO has two separate parts; the first part giv-
       ing the file owner full file privileges,   and the second part allowing anyone
       else to search (but not alter)  the file.   You can expand upon this procedure
       and create even more account sections, and customize each account section in a
       different way.
0      The standard  format $BIBLIO normally  displays records  at the terminal  in a
       line by line format, and requires you to add the words USING APA or USING IEEE
       to the DISPLAY or TYPE commands to see records in a different style.  Two oth-
       er formats,  $BIBLIO.APA and $BIBLIO.IEEE,  are also available and provide the
       same functions  as $BIBLIO;  the only  difference being that they  display re-
       cords,  by default,  in APA or IEEE  styles respectively.   If either of these
       formats is set,  you can still see the line by line form of records by includ-
       ing the words USING PLAIN before the DISPLAY or TYPE command.   As an example,
       suppose you want to arrange it so that accounts who search (but not alter) the
       file automatically see records in APA format.  In the above example, you could
       do this with the following modification:
0        -> modify 464.45
            464.45      SELECT-COMMAND = SET FORMAT $BIBLIO;
            Mods>                                          i.APA
            464.45      SELECT-COMMAND = SET FORMAT $BIBLIO.APA;
            Mods>
         ->
-      As a final modification to the newly created account section, you could insert
       two special  statements which would  hide all  values of the  COMMENTS element
       from public view,  but  still allow the file owner to  add and display private
       comments in bibliographic records.   To include this additional restriction in
       the example, you would type the following:
0        -> insert 464.26 464.27
         464.26 >  constraint = 1;
         464.27 >  noupdate = 1;
         ->
-
0                                          - 44 -
1
-            4.3.7   Other Comments on the Subfile Section
+            4.3.7   Other Comments on the Subfile Section
+                    _____ ________ __ ___ _______ _______
0            In the  subfile section of  your bibliographic subfile  there are a  number of
             SELECT-COMMAND assignment statements.  These statements contain commands which
             are executed automatically whenever you select your bibliographic subfile,  to
             establish the processing environment as described  in this document.   The se-
             lect-commands in the example definition are the following:
0              -> list 459/463
                  459.        SELECT-COMMAND = !SET NOECHO NOSTOP;
                  460.        SELECT-COMMAND = SET COMPXEQ + BIBLIO PROTOCOLS;
                  461.        SELECT-COMMAND = XEQ FROM BIBLIO.MESSAGE;
                  462.        SELECT-COMMAND = SET FORMAT $BIBLIO;
                  463.        SELECT-COMMAND = SET STOP;
               ->
0            The first and last  commands ensure that the environment will  be properly es-
             tablished,  even if you accidentally press the BREAK key.   The second command
             gives you access to the special print protocols described in Section 3 of this
             document.   The third command provides a way for the designer of this applica-
             tion to  notify file owners  of any future  enhancements to the  system.   The
             fourth command sets the main format for  the data base and has been previously
             described.
0            As a final comment and caution,  you are  advised not to attempt to change any
             parts of the file definition other than the subfile sections.  The formats and
             protocols expect record elements to be named  and organized in a specific man-
             ner,  and changing  the file definition may cause these  utilities to function
             improperly.   If  you are seriously considering  a change in the  structure of
             your file, you should see a SPIRES consultant for advice.
